description.narrative: Infants, young children (0-24 months) and mothers particularly those in deprived and hard to reach communities have access to quality maternal, infant and young child nutrition services by end December 2018, which contributes to Infant And Young Child Feeding, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Improved and equitable use of nutritional and care services by communities with a special focus on nutritionally-at-risk children and women residing in the hard to reach areas by end of December 2018

description.narrative: With an additional 2,034 community health workers (CHWs) trained on infant and young child feeding and screening of malnutrition, the percentage of CHWs equipped with nutrition knowledge and skills increased to 75 percent (5,470 out of 7,298) in seven UNICEF-targeted districts. As a result, coverage of quarterly nutrition screening among children under-five increased from 20 percent in 2018 to 35 percent in 2019, including in hard to reach communities. A position paper on the regulation of marketing of breastmilk substitutes is ready for submission to the Parliament. | Status:Met | As-of Date:31/12/2019
